## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement** + **ResetAbort as control flow**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a timed-out thread and `Thread.ResetAbort()` to survive aborts. Both throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Why it breaks

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key changes explained

1. **`CancellationTokenSource(timeout)`** — auto-cancels after the deadline, replacing `Thread.Join` + `Thread.Abort`
2. **`Task.Run`** — replaces manual `Thread` creation; schedules work on the thread pool
3. **`Task.WaitAsync(token)`** (.NET 6+) — blocks synchronously but respects cancellation, replacing `thread.Join(timeout)`
4. **`catch (OperationCanceledException)`** — replaces `catch (ThreadAbortException)`; the `when` guard ensures we only catch timeout-driven cancellation

### Critical pitfall: cancellation is cooperative

Unlike `Thread.Abort`, **cancellation won't interrupt work that doesn't check the token**. If `work` is a long CPU loop or blocking I/O call, it keeps running in the background even after you throw `TimeoutException`.

If your workloads need to actually stop, accept and check a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;
    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller usage:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| **Leaked `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using`/dispose — it holds timer handles |
| **Token not passed through call chain** | Every downstream async/long method must forward it |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores tokens** | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, token)` |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate; only catch at the top-level orchestration point |
| **Uncooperative 3rd-party code** | Move to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()` — only real option for truly uninterruptible work |
